A confounder is a variable that has an influence on both the outcome as well as on treatment assignment. This is a problem because the observed association between treatment and outcome can not be attributed solely to the treatment. Instead, some or even all of the association may be driven by the confounder, which affects both variables. As a result, estimates of treatment effects may be biased or spurious. 

