To still get valid estimates, it is necessary to control for confounding factors. The spurious association between the treatment assignment and the outcome, that the confounders induce, must be removed. Then, only the effect of the treatment on the outcome remains. For this purpose, different approaches have been developed. Most methods, some of which will be introduced in Chapter X,  include the confounders in the model as covariates. To identify variables which influence both treatment assignment and outcome, domain knowledge is often required.

Methods used for treatment effect estimation have different strategies of controlling for confounders. 
